  "prompt": "What is the difference between FRS, PRD, TRD, SRS, MRD, BRD?",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of these software requirements documentation types:\n\n1. FRS (Functional Requirements Specification)\n- Describes the expected functions and features of a system\n- Details what the system should do\n- Focuses on specific functionalities and user interactions\n\n2. PRD (Product Requirements Document)\n- High-level overview of product goals and requirements\n- Includes business objectives, target market, and product vision\n- Covers both functional and non-functional requirements\n\n3. TRD (Technical Requirements Document)\n- Details technical specifications and implementation constraints\n- Describes system architecture, technologies, and technical design\n- Focuses on how the system will be built\n\n4. SRS (Software Requirements Specification)\n- Comprehensive document detailing software requirements\n- Includes functional and non-functional requirements\n- Used as a contract between stakeholders and development team\n\n5. MRD (Market Requirements Document)\n- Defines market opportunities and customer needs\n- Focuses on market research and product positioning\n- Identifies target audience and market potential\n\n6. BRD (Business Requirements Document)\n- Outlines high-level business goals and objectives\n- Defines project scope and expected business outcomes\n- Provides strategic context for the project\n\nEach document serves a different purpose in the software development process, helping to clarify requirements from various perspectives.",
